rect bit?\"\n\nBut wait — that's exactly what my earlier check did, and it failed because `t07` is produced by AND(x07,y07) instead of XOR(x07,y07). The partial sum for bit 7 is t07 (the wire name), but it's produced by the wrong gate.\n\nActually, the correct check should be: \"is the other input wire a wire that was ORIGINALLY meant to be the partial sum for nextBit?\" We can determine this by checking: does the OTHER input to the carry's XOR consumer have the property that there exists an XOR(x(nextBit), y(nextBit)) gate whose output would naturally feed here?\n\nIn the original (unswapped) circuit, the wire `t07` was the output of XOR(x07,y07), and it correctly feeds into XOR(t07,c06). After swap, the gate that produces t07 is now AND(x07,y07), and the gate XOR(x07,y07) now outputs a07. But the consumer gate still references t07.\n\nSo the check I really want is: **is the consumers' other input wire the SAME WIRE as the output of XOR(x(nextBit), y(nextBit))?** In the unswapped case, XOR(x07,y07) produces t07 and the consumer uses t07 → match. In the swapped case (t07<->a07), XOR(x07,y07) produces a07 but the consumer uses t07 → mismatch.\n\nBut this mismatch is caused by the partial sum swap, NOT by a carry swap! The carry c06 is in the right place; it's t07 that's been mislabeled.\n\nThe resolution: **if the expectedPartialSum (a07) is already known to be swapped, then the carry is probably fine.** Let me check: after R3 and other rules, is `a07` in the swapped set?\n\nLet me trace:\n- R3: XOR(x07,y07) -> a07. Bit 7 > 0. Is a07 a z-wire? No. So R3 doesn't flag it.\n- R4: Second-stage XOR check. This gate IS a first-stage XOR (xy inputs), so R4 doesn't apply.\n- R8: First-stage XOR for bit 7. consumers of a07: nobody? Actually, in the original circuit, a07 was the output of AND(x07,y07), consumed by OR(a07,b07). After swap, a07 is the output of XOR(x07,y07). Consumers of a07 are the gates that have a07 as INPUT. In the original circuit: OR(a07, b07) -> z08. So c